          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/lotr/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="0" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Stormcrow at Outpost 2000, 2/23/02<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.73)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4282'>Joshua "Stormcrow" Grace</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=4282&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 26, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> My sister-in-law had an interview for a Physician Assistant&#39;s program in the Twin Cities on Saturday, so my brother called me up to say that he planned to go to Saturday&#39;s LotR CCG tournament. It sounded like fun to me, so I joined the party that eventually included my brother; cousin, Ike; and Ike&#39;s roommate, Jordan.<br>
<br>
We all hung out at Ike&#39;s parents&#39; place in Moose Lake on Friday evening, playing some multi-player, and I tested a deck idea I&#39;d had in mind, using the Strength of Spirit and Barliman Butterbur engine to do massive target archery while A Ranger&#39;s Versatility made easy pickings out of the nastiest minions. Friday evening, my proto-deck walked right through Ike&#39;s defenses and then promptly marched to site 9 against Jordan. However, I just didn&#39;t trust the deck to produce the necessary early-game Gandalf, every game. So I used my generic Arwen and Greenleaf start that also had some target archery, but no Gandalf culture cards.<br>
<br>
For the tournament, Caleb, Ike and I were all playing Arwen and Legolas to start, but Jordan started Gimli and Legolas. My shadow was a Ringwraith and Sauron mixture, Caleb&#39;s was straight Nazgul, Ike&#39;s-I believe-was Uruk-hai, and Jordan was playing a discard strategy with Nobody Tosses a Dwarf, Sauron orcs, Despearate Defense of the Ring and some cards to add burdens.<br>
<br>
There were roughly a dozen players at Outpost 2000, pretty much the same crew that had been at the other tournament I&#39;d attended. Six people were playing a Star Wars tournament that had started earlier in the morning. Only six! Man, that stinks. I would have played in that tournament had my brother not been interested in the LotR tourney. I walk over and say some hellos while my relatives go out to buy food. Dion Erbes, the Star Wars TD, plays a quick game with me, and he doesn&#39;t have Houjix, so 2 or 3 battles of double-digit overflow kill him off before my BHBM can turn Luke. Dion looked disgruntled, and I felt bad about the massacre. But I definitely plan to try the deck in a tournament, soon.<br>
<br>
Anyway, as the time nears for the LotR tourney to start, one of the SW players, Graham, drops from that tournament to play LotR. But he forgot his deck and has to take a bye for the first round while he figures out how to get his deck from his house.<br>
<br>
Game 1:<br>
My archery vs. Chris&#39;s Arwen/Legolas start with Uruk-hai.<br>
<br>
Well, I think that Uruk-hai should be an easy win for me since I can just exhaust the expensive buggers with ARV and tear them apart with archery. Except Chris manages to drop something like 3 Uruk Armories by my 2nd turn, and Lurtz hits the table pretty early, too.<br>
<br>
Well, either Arwen or Legolas died to Lurtz, and that startled me because I wasn&#39;t used to my characters dying (and didn&#39;t have much in the way of back up.) But, meanwhile, after his Legolas exerted twice to down a Nazgul, one of my Sauron orcs expressed his Hatred of the orc, and his company suffered a much more rapid attrition than mine over the next few turns. I managed to cruise to site 7 or 8 with three characters still intact, and Ranger&#39;s Versatility was doing its thing. Chris, however, lost Arwen and Aragorn by site 6, and though he had multiple Bounders, my fierce Nazgul eventually (at site 8) overwhelmed his lone Frodo.<br>
FW 3(3)<br>
<br>
After game 1, I find out that Caleb won, too, and Ike managed his first tournament win (Congrats, Ike!). Jordan lost but had managed to discard his opponent&#39;s entire deck. Unfortunately Jordan&#39;s opponent had enough nastiness in his hand to overwhelm Jordan&#39;s Frodo.<br>
<br>
Graham told me that he had left his deck at Mike Raveling&#39;s place, not his, so he wondered if he could borrow the deck I&#39;d earlier offered to let him borrow. My spare-parts deck, it started Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk and had three copies, each, of the common Legolas, Gimli and Boromir. Two copies of Merry, and Sam came out at the Green Dragon Inn. The Shadow was Uruk-hai, just meant to slow down the opponent, allowing you to remain ahead in the race (always going first). Graham wanted to add 5 cards to each half to tweak it, and once that was done, pairings were called. Graham, of course, got paired against me.<br>
<br>
Game 2:<br>
My stufeasterlingainst my other (spare-parts) stuff, guest-starring Graham Neal.<br>
<br>
Knowing that he needed to bid high to go first but that he didn&#39;t have anything to punish me for accruing burdens, I nearly decided to outbid him. Instead, I decided to bid low, counting on my Nazgul to slow him down while I set up for a double-jumping end run once I got Thror&#39;s Map and Ranger&#39;s Versatility for sites 6 through 9.<br>
<br>
Since Graham went first, I didn&#39;t get the Prancing Pony, but I pulled a Nelya to make things all better. I may have had another Nazgul, too, but Graham had to stop after one movement in order to keep his fellowship alive.<br>
<br>
With the high price of roaming Uruk-hai, Graham couldn&#39;t do much to me as I moved to site 3 on my first turn. And that threw off his whole strategy. He needed to stay ahead of me to win, but, already, I had taken the lead.<br>
<br>
The rest was clockwork. Ranger&#39;s Versatility and archery saw me safely to site 9. Graham was able to recover from his first turn beating and chase after me, but once he gave up the lead, it was over.<br>
FW 3(6)<br>
<br>
After game 2, I knew Caleb had lost, but I started to lose track of Ike and Jordan&#39;s results. After going 3-1 in my first tournament and 2-0 thus far in my second (with the recent acquisition of 10 MORE RARES!) I had some aspirations for the remaining two games, thinking it not entirely impossible that I might win them both…<br>
<br>
New pairings were called, and I got paired up against the guy that beat Caleb, Paul Somebody. Now Paul seemed like a nice guy (don&#39;t get me wrong), but I thought ADHD primarily affected pre-teens and adolescents. In theory, adults lose symptoms… Well, in keeping with the &quot;exception to every rule&quot; rule, Paul was a bit scattered. His attention was literally drawn away from the game at times by shiny cards. (Ah, but that&#39;s okay, too, since after the tournament I traded him a foil There and Back Again and a Greed for a Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk. Thanks, Paul.)<br>
<br>
So, anyway…<br>
<br>
Game 3:<br>
My same-old, same-old against Paul&#39;s Uber-company, starting Gimli and Greenleaf.<br>
<br>
Now, again, my background is in Middle Earth: CCG, so some terms are interchangeable: fellowship (companions) = company, shadow = hazards, fellowship (stuff) = resources, and so on and so forth. Deal with it.<br>
<br>
Paul started by grabbing some burdens for the bid and told me, &quot;I&#39;m going to bid what I always bid.&quot; And I increased my bid to go first, bidding 3 or 4 or something. He bid 1. I decided to go first, and he said that he lost. &quot;I need to go first to win,&quot; he said. Really? Bidding 1? Well, that&#39;s just crazy talk.<br>
<br>
I Pony&#39;d up Aragorn and trucked off, double-moving to site 3. I figured if Paul needs to go first to win, he was just planning to truck on through, himself, and I had better stay a step ahead.<br>
<br>
He tossed out some weak goblins as I moved, and I had no trouble shooting them down with Legolas and Aragorn.<br>
<br>
On Paul&#39;s first turn, however, he tossed out Elrond and Gandalf and moved. That was enough shadow for two fierce Nazgul… If only I had them. Instead, all I had were some trackers and an Under the Watching Eye, which I played. I got a couple of wounds out on him, but nothing that he couldn&#39;t move past. He made it to Rivendell on his first turn, wounded, but alive.<br>
<br>
I wiped out all his goblins at site 4 and, guessing that the game would just be a pure race, I double-moved into The Bridge of Khazad-dum. I probably won&#39;t do that again (with the Balrog coming out), but, even though he tossed out 6 or 7 orcs, they were nothing that Legolas and Aragorn couldn&#39;t handle. The twang of bowstrings resonated once more through the caverns of Moria. There was one of those &quot;camera follows the arrow&quot; shots as Legolas decided that any Wallcrawler hoping to reduce the archery total ought to just die before there is any archery total. So he shot it.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately for me, even though I&#39;d upped the ante by double-moving into The Bridge of Khazad-dum, I was still drawing a thin hazard hand while Paul was adding Aragorn, Boromir, Arwen and maybe Merry to his company. Yeesh! He could run through my minions and keep Frodo a mile away from a skirmish… Which he did, double-jumping to the Bridge of Khazad-dum with a wound here and another wound there and such, but he had enough characters to take the hits that none were in any imminent peril.<br>
<br>
On my next turn, I raced past Lorien, still largely free of wounds and lucked out when he didn&#39;t play the site that skipped the archery phase. Again, he followed.<br>
<br>
At this point, I still hadn&#39;t draw my Thror&#39;s Map and knew that I would need to play my site 8 to get past it on my next turn. But I failed to draw it, and Paul spotted 5 orcs before they all died to my bows and swords.<br>
<br>
I played all the cards I could and discarded to draw an extra card, hoping for anything to stop his movement, but against his 8 characters, there just wasn&#39;t anything I could do. He gave two wounds to the Witch-king in archery at site 8 and then killed him with PATHS. At site 9, I played a Nazgul or two and then 3 trackers with Tol Brandir&#39;s text, but I couldn&#39;t even force Frodo to face a strike. (Update: Yeah, that move with PATHS has prompted me to ditch the Nazgul/Sauron combo and just concentrate on working one culture-Nazgul-to greater effect, namely by including All Blades Perish.)<br>
FL 1(7)<br>
<br>
Well, there were still two undefeated players, Emanuel, who had overwhelmed all his opponents by site 3, and Paul. First place would be determined in their last-round match-up, then. Meanwhile, there was a chance I could still go 3-1, matching my first tournament&#39;s performance, and tie for second (because the store owner just doesn&#39;t do tie-breakers, it seems).<br>
<br>
My chance for redemption proved also to be a chance for revenge. I was paired up against Big Red. If you haven&#39;t read my first tournament report, Big Red was the winner of my first tournament after he defeated me in the last round, overwhelming my Frodo even as I was killing off his companions, one by one.<br>
<br>
This time, I listened more closely to pairings and learned that Big Red&#39;s name is Brian. But that&#39;s not half as interesting, so he&#39;ll remain Big Red, so dubbed for his long, red hair, red-tinted beard and large, leather-jacketed self. Harley-Davidson meets Lord of the Rings.<br>
<br>
Anyway, my hopes for victory were quickly, neatly and mercilessly squashed. I outbid Big Red to go first and played Aragorn with the Pony. Unfortunately, I had no other resources to play from my hand, so when I moved to encounter two fierce Nazgul (thanks to Morgul Gates) and three Blade Tips, I was already headed for the graveyard. I double-jumped, then, hoping to survive to Rivendell for the healing. I made it there, but Legolas, Arwen, and Aragorn were all wounded and pierced by shadow blades.<br>
<br>
I didn&#39;t have anything equally fantastic to hit Big Red immediately, but he only had Gandalf and Frodo. He stopped at site 2 after an orc wounded Gandalf. He didn&#39;t need to move, though. I had to carry on toward imminent doom. Aragorn managed to find some Athelas to chew and cure himself of the blade&#39;s effect, but Arwen merely had to find consolation in his encouragement (King in Exile, &quot;The hands of the king are the hands of a healer.&quot;). Legolas, however, wasn&#39;t quite so fortunate, and recognizing the weird that was upon him, sacrificed himself for the others at site 5 where another two fierce Nazgul attacked. (Meanwhile, I had to wonder if Big Red ever got tired of double-teaming people with his fierce Nazgul… Yeesh.)<br>
<br>
Big Red just plodded along while his Frodo cowered from a couple of Nazgul. His company grew and suffered wounds and moved slowly, and I had to keep pressing forward, eventually reaching site 7 with just Aragorn and Frodo. Yet another fierce Nazgul killed the exhausted Dunadan, and then turned to the cowering Hobbit to rend him in twain.<br>
FL 1(8)<br>
Yea! Verily, the Ring went back to Big Red&#39;s Sauron yet once more. And all the lands were covered in darkness.<br>
<br>
Still, apart from the paucity of my opening hand, it proved to be an entertaining game, and Big Red is a fairly low-key, pleasant opponent.<br>
<br>
Thus, I finished a mere 2-2, but Caleb had rallied and went 3-1 to tie for second, en masse. Ike and Jordan each finished 1-3. Emanuel beat Paul in the last confrontation of undefeated players to take first.<br>
<br>
Our little entourage engaged in a furious flury of fast-paced trading. We stopped for dinner at a Perkins in Forest Lake, and I slapped together my target archery deck to play against Caleb. I couldn&#39;t draw Gandalf to save Frodo&#39;s life… I was at site 6, I think, before I saw him, and, of course, my hand was clogged causing me to lose horribly. So, perhaps, I figured, I may have made the better choice for a tournament deck, despite my performance, but I&#39;ve got to figure out something better yet (that I can make with my, now, 30 or so rares).<br>
<br>
Until next time,<br>
<br>
Walk with Eru,<br>
Joshua &quot;Stormcrow&quot; Grace<br>
